<h1 id=3D"Chapter-6-Regression">Chapter 6 Regression<a class=3D"anchor-link=
" href=3D"https://datascience.tamucc.edu/user/ljin1/files/Spr2026/MATH5341/=
DASC5341_Chapter6a.html#Chapter-6-Regression">=C2=B6</a></h1><p>Regression =
to model the relationship between the response and a few independent variab=
les. Linear regression, the relationship is linear.</p>
<h2 id=3D"6.1-Simple-Linear-regression">6.1 Simple Linear regression<a clas=
s=3D"anchor-link" href=3D"https://datascience.tamucc.edu/user/ljin1/files/S=
pr2026/MATH5341/DASC5341_Chapter6a.html#6.1-Simple-Linear-regression">=C2=
=B6</a></h2><p>Simple linear regression is a statistical method used to pre=
dict a continuous response variable from a single explanatory variable. For=
 example, consider the <code>cars</code> data in R, where <code>speed</code=
> represents a car=E2=80=99s speed and <code>dist</code> represents its sto=
pping distance.</p>
<p>If a car were selected at random, one simple guess for its stopping dist=
ance would be the overall mean stopping distance for all cars in the datase=
t. This might be a reasonable starting point if no other information were a=
vailable. However, such a guess would often be inaccurate because cars trav=
eling at different speeds are expected to have different stopping distances=
.</p>
<p>Since stopping distance is related to speed, we can improve prediction b=
y using speed as an explanatory variable. A statistical method that takes a=
dvantage of this relationship is simple linear regression.</p>
<p>The term <em>simple</em> linear regression means that the model includes=
 only one explanatory variable. In this example, <code>speed</code> is the =
explanatory variable, and <code>dist</code> is the response variable. The g=
oal is to describe how stopping distance changes with speed and to use that=
 relationship to predict stopping distance for a given speed.</p>
<p>The statistical model for simple linear regression is</p>
