<h2 id=3D"Model-checking">Model checking<a class=3D"anchor-link" href=3D"ht=
tps://datascience.tamucc.edu/user/ljin1/files/Spr2026/MATH5341/DASC5341_Cha=
pter6a.html#Model-checking">=C2=B6</a></h2><p>After fitting a simple linear=
 regression model, it is important to check whether the model assumptions a=
re reasonable. Model checking helps us determine whether the fitted regress=
ion line provides an appropriate description of the relationship between th=
e explanatory variable and the response variable. If the assumptions are no=
t satisfied, then the estimates, tests, confidence intervals, and predictio=
ns from the model may not be reliable.</p>
<p>A useful first step is to examine a <strong>scatterplot</strong> of the =
response variable versus the explanatory variable before fitting the model.=
 The scatterplot helps us assess whether the relationship appears approxima=
tely linear. If the points follow a roughly straight-line pattern, then a s=
imple linear regression model may be appropriate. On the other hand, if the=
 pattern is curved or highly irregular, then a linear model may not fit the=
 data well. After fitting the model, it is also helpful to add the fitted r=
egression line to the scatterplot to see whether the line captures the over=
all trend in the data.</p>
<p>Another important step is to examine the <strong>residuals</strong>, whi=
ch are the differences between the observed values and the fitted values. A=
 plot of residuals versus the fitted values, or residuals versus the explan=
atory variable, can be used to check whether the variance appears roughly c=
onstant and whether there are signs of nonlinearity. Ideally, the residuals=
 should be randomly scattered around zero with no clear pattern. If the spr=
ead of the residuals increases or decreases as the fitted values increase, =
then the constant variance assumption may be violated. If a curved pattern =
appears, then the linearity assumption may not hold.</p>
<p>The <strong>normality assumption</strong> is commonly checked by using a=
 histogram of residuals, a normal Q-Q plot, or a formal normality test such=
 as the <strong>Shapiro-Wilk test</strong>. If the residuals are approximat=
ely normal, then the points in the Q-Q plot should lie close to a straight =
line. The Shapiro-Wilk test can also be used to test the null hypothesis th=
at the residuals come from a normal distribution. A large p-value suggests =
that the normality assumption is reasonable, while a very small p-value sug=
gests departure from normality. However, the normality test should be inter=
preted together with the plots, since formal tests can be sensitive to samp=
le size.</p>
<p>It is also important to check for <strong>unusual observations</strong>,=
 such as outliers or influential points. An outlier is an observation with =
an unusually large residual, while an influential observation is one that h=
as a strong effect on the fitted regression line. Such points can sometimes=
 distort the estimated relationship and affect the regression results. Diag=
nostic plots and influence measures can help identify these observations fo=
r further investigation.</p>
<p>In addition, if the data are collected over time or in sequence, the <st=
rong>independence</strong> of the errors should be considered. For time-ord=
ered data, residuals may be correlated with one another, which violates a b=
asic regression assumption. In such cases, plotting the residuals in their =
data collection order may help reveal patterns or dependence. If strong dep=
endence is present, a different modeling approach may be needed.</p>
<p>Overall, model checking is an essential part of regression analysis. A f=
itted model should not be accepted only because the regression equation has=
 been obtained. Instead, graphical and numerical diagnostics should be used=
 to verify that the assumptions of linearity, constant variance, normality,=
 and independence are reasonably satisfied.</p>

