/datasets/fat.txt">http://jse.amstat.org/datasets/fat.txt</a>.</p>
<p>The bodyfat data set contains observations on 252 men, including body fa=
t percentages estimated from underwater weighing and a set of body measurem=
ents such as age, weight, height, and body circumferences. The response var=
iables are brozek and siri, two formulas for estimating percent body fat fr=
om body density, while the remaining variables are potential predictors. Th=
e data were discussed in Johnson (1996), based on earlier work by Penrose, =
Nelson, and Fisher (1985), and are widely used for regression examples. A f=
ew recording errors are known to exist in the data, including some incorrec=
t density values and at least one implausible height measurement.</p>
<p>Use BodyFat (percentage of body fat) as the response variable.</p>
<p>Do not include Density as a predictor, because body fat percentage is ca=
lculated from body density, so it carries essentially the same information =
and would make the model inappropriate. If your dataset contains both Siri =
and Brozek body fat measures, choose only one of them as the response and d=
o not use the other as a predictor.</p>
